ce:section.ce:para:
Section 4.3 reveal that convective heat transfer in supercritical temperature is low and keeping fluid temperature in lower and close to critical temperature can improve heat transfer coefficient by taking advantage on the thermophysical properties. Therefore, it is of interest to vary the inlet mass flux of the sCO2 flow between 100 kg/m2·s and 200 kg/m2·s to evaluate its effect onto the investigated convective heat transfer. Comparing the wall and bulk temperatures for the base case (Fig. 10a) and increased mass flux in Fig. 12
(a) and (b), the temperature rises slower with the increase on the mass flux due to a shorter residence time in the tubes and more mass of fluid to distribute the heat input from the wall. The distance from inlet required to reach critical temperature is increased, where 200 kg/m2·s case only have their bulk temperature reach critical temperature at the end of the tube. Another thing to be noticed is the difference between wall temperature and bulk temperature decreases when the mass flux increases. This is reflected in the heat transfer coefficients in Figs. 10(b), 12(c) and (d). The heat transfer coefficient increases about 85 % and 50 % as the mass flux increases from 100 kg/m2·s to 150 kg/m2·s and 150 kg/m2·s to 200 kg/m2·s, respectively (Table 5
). This is probably because of slow temperature build up in higher mass flux, which makes the carbon dioxide fluid to stay at high thermal conductivity and high specific heat capacity for a longer period in the tube as the bulk temperature is approaching critical temperature. The high specific heat capacity further magnifies the heat transfer enhancement outcome by keeping the temperature near the pseudo-critical longer with relatively high thermal conductivity. The combined effect of tape width and mass flux are showing clearer trend in Table 5, where the heat transfer rates are slightly increased in general. It shows that narrower width is more favorable at the thermophysical before pseudo-critical temperature. For the pressure drop, as expected, the pressure drops increase as the mass flux increases, because the pressure difference needs to be larger to drive the flow faster across the tube.
